As of 15-Oct-2015, there's an estimated >475k sea arrivals (for 2015), to Greece alone, which is quite impressive considering that, by the end of June the number of estimated arrivals was ~68k. Of these:
- >260k people have arrived to Lesvos, which is ~12-15-kilometres away from (Turkey). AFR claims that refugees/migrants have shifted to this route from routes hundreds of miles south (around Bodrum) sometime in August.
- >62k have arrived to Samos
- >44kk have arrived to Kos
- >57k have arrived to Chios Even if Turkey and the EU reach some agreement on visa-free travel to the EU, for Turkish citizens + EU financial support, in exchange for Turkey stemming the flow of migrants, it's not very clear what Turkey can do in the short term, to reduce the migrants' flow, especially considering that:
- its sea border with Greece is about 1000km long and intertwined with hundreds of islands;
- the migrants/refugees seem to have been quite resourceful, in the recent past, to adjusting/finding new routes; The weather forecast doesn't look bad at all, at least for for the next week, for the main Greek islands:
- Lesvos (16C - 24C);
- Chios (16C - 24C);
- Samos (18C - 26C);
- Kos (17C - 28C); Several resources exist that provide numbers (estimates) on the refugees/migrants arriving by sea, including: 
- UNHCR; 
- the International Organization for Migration (IOM);
- the European Agency for the Management of Operational Cooperation at the External Borders of the Member States of the European Union (Frontex);
etc The numbers seem to be adjusted/revised at times, by considerable margins (e.g.: UNHCR has decreased, in the past 48 hours, the estimate for September by exactly 15,000: from 187,843 to 172,843). The numbers don't align across the different sources (e.g.: IOM's recent estimates are within 10-15% range from the UNHCR etimates) even when the measurement methodologies are the same (probably b/c they have been collected at different dates?). Several measurement/estimation methodologies are used, e.g.:
- the IOM numbers for Greece are not the actual daily arrivals but the number of migrants who have officially been recorded by the Greek authorities after their arrival;
- UNHCR provides data collected in a similar fashion but also compiles direct Direct Observational Data / Anecdotal Data;
etc Fitting autoregressive integrated moving averages models (on IOM, UNHCR, Frontex data), to try to estimate the number of arrivals by the end of October, seems to provide a wide range of values (132k-229k). A few links:
